<!-- SECTION 2: OVERVIEW / INTRO + TL;DR -->
<section class="content-section" id="overview-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Foreign Branch Office Setup from Delhi - Overview</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-bottom:20px;">
                    <p><strong>&#128204; TL;DR - Foreign Branch Office Setup Services at a Glance</strong></p>
                    <p>A branch office of a foreign company in India is an extension of the overseas parent, set up under FEMA 1999 and the 2016 Regulations. Approval is obtained on Form FNC through an Authorized Dealer Category-I bank; the Reserve Bank of India allots a Unique Identification Number, after which Form FC-1 is filed with the ROC within 30 days under Section 380 Companies Act 2013.</p>
                </div>
                <p><div class='table-responsive-wrapper'>
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Quick Reference</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Governing Law</td><td>Foreign Exchange Management Act 1999 and FEMA (Establishment in India of a Branch Office, Liaison Office, Project Office or any other Place of Business) Regulations 2016 (Draft 2025 Regulations released October 2025 - NOT yet notified as of June 2026; 2016 framework continues to apply)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Applicable To</td><td>Foreign corporate bodies seeking a commercial presence in India without setting up a separate Indian legal entity</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Timeline</td><td>AD bank or RBI approval 4-8 weeks (automatic route); 8-12 weeks (government route or Press Note 3 (2020) cases); ROC Form FC-1 within 30 days of approval; overall 45-90 days standard; 90-120 days sensitive sectors</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Cost (Indicative)</td><td>Hub 12 cross-list. Patron fees - BO end-to-end INR 49,999 starting, LO alternative INR 39,999 starting, PO alternative INR 34,999 starting. Annual AAC INR 9,999 + ROC FC-3/FC-4 INR 7,499 + branch ITR INR 14,999 per year. Statutory charges at actuals</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Tax Rate / Penalty</td><td>Branch profits taxed at 40% plus surcharge and education cess (foreign company rate). PE-equivalent treatment under most tax treaties; equalisation levy, GST, TDS apply. FEMA Section 13 compounding INR 2,000 to 3x sum involved</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Forms / Portal</td><td>Form FNC (RBI / AD bank); Form FC-1 with ROC under Section 380 Companies Act 2013; AAC by 30 September; Form FC-3 + FC-4 annually; PAN, TAN, AD bank account, GST post-UIN</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Authority</td><td>Reserve Bank of India, AD Category-I Bank, Registrar of Companies Delhi, Income Tax Department (International Taxation), DPIIT and line ministry for sectoral approvals</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div></p>
                <p>A branch office is the most direct route for a foreign company to undertake commercial activities in India without incorporating a separate Indian entity, and Delhi-NCR remains the largest hub for these offices because of its proximity to the Ministry of Finance, the Ministry of External Affairs, the Ministry of Commerce and Industry and DPIIT. Under the FEMA framework, the parent company files Form FNC with an Authorized Dealer Category-I bank, which forwards the application to the Reserve Bank of India where approval is required. The RBI allots a Unique Identification Number, and within 30 days of receiving the approval letter, the company files Form FC-1 with the Registrar of Companies under Section 380 of the Companies Act 2013.</p>
                <p>Content is reviewed quarterly for accuracy.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 3: WHAT IS GSTAT APPEAL FILING -->
<section class="content-section" id="what-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="two-column">
            <div class="column-content">
                <h2 class="section-title">What Is a Branch Office of a Foreign Company in India?</h2>
                <div class="content-text what-is-definition">
                    
                    <p>A branch office of a foreign company in India is an office set up by a body corporate incorporated outside India, under the <strong>Foreign Exchange Management Act 1999</strong>, to carry out specified commercial activities permitted by the Reserve Bank of India. It is NOT a separate legal entity; it remains an extension of the foreign parent, and the parent assumes full liability for its Indian operations.</p>

<p>Approval is sought on <strong>Form FNC</strong> routed through an Authorized Dealer Category-I bank; for sensitive sectors or non-100-percent FDI activities the application moves to RBI for case-by-case decision in consultation with the Government of India. Once approved, the RBI allots a <strong>Unique Identification Number (UIN)</strong>, and the office must register with the Registrar of Companies Delhi by filing <strong>Form FC-1 within 30 days</strong> under Section 380 of the Companies Act 2013.</p>

<p>Three sister vehicles exist under the same FEMA Regulations 2016 framework:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Branch Office (BO):</strong> Commercial office permitted to undertake specified activities; can issue invoices and earn revenue; 5-year profit track record + USD 100,000 net worth threshold.</li>
    <li><strong>Liaison Office (LO):</strong> Representative office restricted to non-commercial activities; cannot earn income; 3-year track record + USD 50,000 net worth.</li>
    <li><strong>Project Office (PO):</strong> Temporary office for executing a specific project in India under contract with an Indian company.</li>
</ul>

<p>Branch Offices are NOT permitted to undertake retail trading of any nature, or manufacturing or processing activities directly, except in Special Economic Zones for sectors where 100 percent FDI is allowed. Foreign legal practice is also prohibited. The Wholly Owned Subsidiary route via MCA SPICe+ incorporation is the alternative where commercial reach requires full legal entity status.</p>

<p>Branch profits are taxed at <strong>40% plus surcharge and education cess</strong> under the Income Tax Act 1961 - the foreign company rate. The branch is treated as a Permanent Establishment of the foreign parent under most tax treaties, with transfer pricing rules (Sections 92 to 92F + Form 3CEB) applying to intra-group transactions.</p>

<p>The <strong>Draft Foreign Exchange Management (Establishment in India of a branch or office) Regulations 2025</strong> were released by RBI on 3 October 2025 for public consultation but are NOT yet notified as of June 2026 - the 2016 framework continues to apply.</p>

<p>Delhi anchors this engagement because of access to ROC Delhi, the Income Tax International Taxation circles, AD Category-I bank head offices and proximity to the central ministries and DPIIT that hold sectoral approval authority.</p>

                </div>
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:20px;">
                    <p><strong>Key Terms for Foreign Branch Office Setup:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Branch Office (BO):</strong> Commercial office of a foreign company in India permitted to undertake activities specified by RBI; can issue invoices and earn revenue.</p>
<p><strong>Liaison Office (LO):</strong> Representative office restricted to non-commercial activities such as parent representation and information exchange.</p>
<p><strong>Project Office (PO):</strong> Temporary office for executing a specific project in India under contract with an Indian company.</p>
<p><strong>Form FNC:</strong> Application form filed with the AD Category-I bank for RBI approval to set up a branch, liaison or project office in India.</p>
<p><strong>Form FC-1:</strong> ROC registration form filed under Section 380 Companies Act 2013 by a foreign company establishing a place of business in India.</p>
<p><strong>UIN:</strong> Unique Identification Number - allotted by RBI to each approved branch, liaison or project office for FEMA tracking.</p>
<p><strong>AD Category-I Bank:</strong> Authorized Dealer Category-I bank empowered by RBI to receive Form FNC, conduct due diligence and (for 100% FDI sectors) approve the application.</p>
<p><strong>AAC:</strong> Annual Activity Certificate - yearly compliance filing certifying activities carried on during the FY; due by 30 September.</p>
<p><strong>Form FC-3:</strong> Annual financial statements filing with ROC by a foreign company under Companies (Registration of Foreign Companies) Rules 2014.</p>
<p><strong>Form FC-4:</strong> Annual return filing with ROC by a foreign company.</p>
<p><strong>Press Note 3 (2020):</strong> DPIIT Press Note imposing Government Approval route for FDI from countries sharing a land border with India; adds 8-12 weeks to BO setup timeline.</p>
<p><strong>Letter of Comfort (LOC):</strong> Letter from a financially sound parent supporting a subsidiary applicant not meeting the USD 100,000 net worth threshold.</p>

                </div>
            </div>
