<section class="content-section" id="documents-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Documents Checklist for Branch Office Setup in Delhi</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <ul>
                    <li>Certificate of Incorporation of the foreign company - notarised and apostilled (Hague Convention countries) or Indian Embassy attested (non-Hague Convention countries)</li>
                    <li>MOA and AOA (or equivalent charter) of the foreign parent - same legalisation</li>
                    <li>Latest 5 years audited financial statements of the parent - English translation with CA / equivalent certification</li>
                    <li>Banker's report from the parent's overseas banker confirming banking relationship and standing</li>
                    <li>Board resolution authorising the establishment of the Indian branch and appointing the authorised signatory and Indian authorised representative</li>
                    <li>Power of Attorney in favour of the authorised signatory for Form FNC (where not signed by the head of the entity)</li>
                    <li>Letter of Comfort from the parent (where the applicant is a subsidiary relying on the parent's net worth)</li>
                    <li>Proposed Indian office address proof in Delhi - rent agreement, NOC and latest utility bill</li>
                    <li>KYC and identity proof of the authorised representative in India</li>
                    <li>Detailed business activity write-up and 3-year projected financials for the Indian operations</li>
                    <li>Net worth certificate from CA / equivalent in home country confirming USD 100,000+ (paid-up capital + free reserves - intangible assets)</li>
                    <li>Press Note 3 (2020) disclosure pack where applicable (applicants from land-border countries)</li>
                </ul>

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 9: CHALLENGES -->
<section class="content-section" id="challenges-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Common Delhi-NCR Challenges and Patron Solutions</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="table-responsive-wrapper">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Impact</th><th>How Patron Accounting Solves It</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Parent's 5-year profit track record borderline or loss year due to consolidation accounting</td><td>The eligibility requires uninterrupted 5-year profit track record but consolidation accounting (group restructuring, one-off impairments, foreign exchange losses) can introduce a loss year that disqualifies an otherwise sound applicant.</td><td>Patron restates the position with a CA reconciliation note explaining the loss, supplements with the Letter of Comfort from a financially sound group entity and pre-clears with the AD bank prior to formal Form FNC submission. Avoids rejection-and-resubmit cycles.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Proposed activity falls outside automatic 100% FDI</td><td>For digital media, multi-brand retail trading, defence and other sectors where 100% FDI is not on the automatic route, the file moves to RBI in consultation with line ministry and DPIIT - adding 4-8 weeks to the timeline.</td><td>Patron positions the file for the RBI review track, prepares the inter-ministerial memo for DPIIT or the line ministry and aligns the activity description with the closest permitted activity. Where retail trading is involved Patron recommends a wholly owned subsidiary route as an alternative.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Applicant from a land-border country (Press Note 3 (2020))</td><td>DPIIT Press Note 3 of 2020 imposes Government Approval route for FDI from countries sharing a land border with India (China, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nepal, Bhutan, Myanmar, Afghanistan). Adds 8-12 weeks to BO setup timeline.</td><td>Patron prepares the Press Note 3 disclosure pack, routes through the Government Approval channel and coordinates with the line ministry. Timeline expectations set transparently at engagement. Sensitive sector overlay handled where applicable.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Documents from the home country not in English or not apostilled</td><td>FEMA requires English-language documents with proper legalisation. Documents in original language (German, Japanese, Mandarin, Arabic, Russian) or without Hague Convention apostille fail AD bank document verification on first submission.</td><td>Patron coordinates with Delhi-based translation and apostille partners, walks the original documents through the home-country notary and apostille (or Indian Embassy attestation if not a Hague Convention country) and avoids repeat AD bank queries.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>30-day Form FC-1 deadline missed</td><td>Companies Act 2013 Section 380 + Rule 3 of Companies (Registration of Foreign Companies) Rules 2014 imposes 30-day hard deadline for Form FC-1 filing post-approval. Missing it triggers penalties and downstream PAN, TAN, GST, bank account issues since these all require FC-1 acknowledgement.</td><td>Patron's Delhi ROC-side team locks the FC-1 filing into the master calendar at AD bank approval - Form FC-1 is drafted in parallel with the AD bank approval cycle so filing happens within 5-10 days of approval letter receipt, not at the 30-day edge.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>October 2025 Draft Regulations release</td><td>RBI released the Draft Foreign Exchange Management (Establishment in India of a branch or office) Regulations 2025 on 3 October 2025 for public consultation but NOT yet notified as of June 2026. Foreign parents are unsure whether to file under the 2016 framework or wait.</td><td>Patron's advisory surfaces the trade-off transparently - the 2016 framework continues to apply, so structures should be filed without waiting; but for marginal cases (borderline eligibility, complex sector mapping) the Draft 2025 framework may offer better terms when notified. Forward-looking advice given based on the parent's timeline.</td></tr>

                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

