                <div class="faq-expanded__list">
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-1">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How can a foreign company open a branch office in India?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>A foreign body corporate files Form FNC with an Authorized Dealer Category-I bank, supported by the certificate of incorporation, latest five years audited financials, banker report and board resolution. The AD bank conducts due diligence; for 100 percent FDI sectors it approves directly, otherwise the file goes to the Reserve Bank of India. After approval and Unique Identification Number allotment, Form FC-1 is filed with the Registrar of Companies Delhi within 30 days under Section 380 of the Companies Act 2013.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-2">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the difference between a branch office and a liaison office?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>A branch office is permitted to undertake specified commercial activities under FEMA, can issue invoices and earn revenue in India. A liaison office is restricted to non-commercial representative activities such as parent representation and information exchange; it cannot earn any income in India and is funded entirely by inward remittances from the parent. Net worth and track record thresholds also differ - USD 100,000 and 5 years for a branch versus USD 50,000 and 3 years for a liaison office.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-3">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How long does it take to set up a branch office in India?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Typical end-to-end timeline is 45 to 90 days. Document legalisation in the home country takes 1 to 3 weeks, AD bank KYC and due diligence 1 to 2 weeks, RBI or AD bank approval 4 to 8 weeks under the automatic route, and ROC Form FC-1 filing within 30 days of approval. Press Note 3 (2020) cases and sensitive sectors extend the timeline to 90-120 days.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-4">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What activities are not permitted for a branch office?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>A branch office cannot undertake retail trading of any nature, manufacturing or processing activities directly (except in Special Economic Zones for sectors with 100 percent FDI) or the practice of Indian law. Activities falling under the FDI approval route, or any activity not expressly permitted by the RBI in the approval letter, are also prohibited.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-5">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How is a branch office of a foreign company taxed in India?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>A branch office is treated as a permanent establishment of the foreign parent under most tax treaties. Net income earned in India is taxed at 40 percent plus applicable surcharge and education cess, the foreign company rate prescribed under the Income Tax Act 1961. GST, TDS, equalisation levy (where relevant) and transfer pricing rules (Sections 92 to 92F with Form 3CEB) also apply.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-6">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the net worth requirement for opening a branch office?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>The foreign parent must have a net worth of not less than USD 100,000 or its equivalent, calculated as paid-up capital plus free reserves less intangible assets, supported by the latest audited balance sheet certified by a Chartered Accountant or equivalent in the home jurisdiction. A subsidiary not meeting the threshold can apply with a Letter of Comfort from a financially sound parent.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-7">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is Form FNC and Form FC-1?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Form FNC is the application form filed with the AD Category-I bank for RBI approval to set up a branch, liaison or project office in India. Form FC-1 is the ROC registration form filed under Section 380 of the Companies Act 2013 by a foreign company that establishes a place of business in India - filed within 30 days of receiving the AD bank approval letter.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-8">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Can a branch office repatriate profits to the parent company?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Yes. A branch office can remit net profits to the foreign parent after payment of applicable Indian taxes. The AD bank effects the remittance on production of the audited balance sheet and profit and loss account, a certificate from a Chartered Accountant confirming the manner of arriving at the remittable amount and proof of payment of all applicable taxes including transfer pricing-aligned positions where intra-group transactions occur.</p></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

